\begin{abstract}
We introduce AMF Hash, a deterministic hashing method that represents hash values using a structured quotient--remainder decomposition, referred to as AMF Division. Unlike conventional hash functions that produce a single scalar output, AMF Hash yields a pair $(q, r)$ capturing coarse and fine components of the hash space. This approach enables a multi-level interpretation of hash outputs and may be useful in structured data partitioning and hierarchical indexing. We formalize the method, analyze its properties, and discuss its computational characteristics and limitations.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Hash functions play a central role in computer science, particularly in data structures, distributed systems, and data integrity mechanisms \cite{knuth1998, cormen2009}. Traditional hash functions map inputs to scalar values.

In contrast, we propose a structured representation:
\[
\text{Hash}(D) \rightarrow (q, r)
\]
where the output is decomposed via quotient--remainder arithmetic. This representation introduces a two-level structure in the hash space.

\section{AMF Hash Definition}

Let:
\[
D = (d_0, d_1, \dots, d_{n-1}), \quad d_i \in [0,255]
\]

Define:
\[
H(D) = n + \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} (d_i + \alpha)(i+1)
\]
where $n = |D|$ and $\alpha$ is a constant offset (e.g., 129).

\section{AMF Division}

Let $M \in \mathbb{N}, M > 0$. Then:
\[
H(D) = Mq + r
\quad \text{with} \quad 0 \le r < M
\]

\subsection{Definition}

\[
\operatorname{AMFHash}_M(D) = (q, r)
\]

\subsection{Equivalent Form}

\[
\frac{H(D)}{M} = q + \frac{r}{M}
\]

This representation follows classical Euclidean division \cite{hardy1979}.

\section{Interpretation}

The pair $(q, r)$ provides a hierarchical structure:

\begin{itemize}
\item $q$: coarse partition component
\item $r$: fine-grained residue
\end{itemize}

\section{Illustrative Structure}

The structured representation can be visualized conceptually:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{c|c}
Component & Role \\
\hline
$q$ & Global partition index \\
$r$ & Local offset within partition \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

This interpretation enables multi-level indexing schemes.

\section{Example}

Let:
\[
D = \text{"ABC"} = [65, 66, 67]
\]

\[
H(D) = 3 + (65+129)\cdot1 + (66+129)\cdot2 + (67+129)\cdot3
\]

\[
H(D) = 1175
\]

Let $M = 100$:
\[
1175 = 100 \cdot 11 + 75
\]

\[
\operatorname{AMFHash}_{100}(D) = (11, 75)
\]

\section{Properties}

\subsection{Determinism}
The function is deterministic.

\subsection{Time Complexity}
\[
O(n)
\]

\subsection{Uniqueness}
The decomposition is unique for fixed $M$.

\subsection{Reconstruction}
\[
H(D) = Mq + r
\]

\section{Applications}

\subsection{Data Partitioning}
$q$ may determine storage nodes, while $r$ determines local placement.

\subsection{Structured Hash Tables}
Supports hierarchical indexing.

\subsection{Multi-Scale Analysis}
Enables coarse-to-fine interpretation of hash values.

\section{Limitations}

\begin{itemize}
\item Not a cryptographic hash function \cite{menezes1996}
\item No formal collision resistance guarantees
\item Linear structure may produce predictable patterns
\end{itemize}

\section{Authorship and Origin}

AMF Division and AMF Hash were introduced by Alexandre Martins de Freitas (2026).

The formulation builds upon classical Euclidean division:
\[
a = bq + r, \quad 0 \le r < |b|
\]

The contribution lies in its structured representation and application to hashing.

\section{Conclusion}

AMF Hash provides a structured alternative to scalar hash representations. By decomposing hash outputs into quotient and remainder components, it enables multi-level interpretation and potential applications in partitioned systems and hierarchical indexing.

